text: (during the trailer) *Older me:* No.......why this? *Child me:* Yay! *Older me:* They look creepy! *Child me:* Yet they sound endearing. *Older me:* Well they did get Jim Cummings. Why am I complimenting this? Piglet doesn't sound right! *Child me:* They left off on the dialogue from Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh! *Older me:* Please don't send them in our world. *Child me:* I don't care, I like this! *Older me:* Bankers who keep workers from families and hate what's "most unorthodox"? How cliched.  *Child me:* This is grown up Christopher Robin done right!  *Older me:* Well this is what I wanted from Tim Burton's Alice in Wonderland, rediscovering childhood. *Me:* OH WHO AM I KIDDING? This is beautiful! I don't care if some things are cliched or if the characters look a little creepy; I'm going to see this! This is what I would want to see in a person rediscovering childhood done right so far!

text: No one could do Piglet's voice like the late John Fiedler. I remember in high school watching the Sidney Portier version of 'A Raisin in the Sun' and when Fiedler's character comes on screen, everyone was trying to recall where they had heard that voice before. It took a few minutes to identify (just because it's a live action production), but I was a fan of The New Adventures of Winnie the Pooh--and apparently so was everyone else. When I said, "That's Piglet!" The room erupted with "Oh yeah!" and such a sense of delight. So many from that series have past on & with no official DVD release or behind the scenes interviews (etc.), they never got the credit they deserved for creating such a magical & wonderful experience through that show. It still holds up too!

Like I never thought about it, but everyone keeps bringing up how they get nostalgic and stuff from watching this because it reminds them of their childhood. You know you were a good writer when you make a bunch of 14+ (estimating) age people cry from just hearing Winnie the Pooh's voice. Congrats A.A. text: I honestly don't want to see this film, not because it doesn't look good, but because I'm not sure how many live action "down to earth" representations of classic children's properties I can take. For example, I would have to say that "Saving Mr. Banks" was a great film and Tom Hanks did an awesome Job as Walt Disney. But I would be lying to myself if I said that I didn't come out of that movie super depressed considering the way they depicted the real family of the author. And I would say the same for that one movie about the author of Peter Pan (I forget it's name) and the more recent representation of Winnie the Pooh "Goodbye Christopher Robin". Which I also thought was a great film. And I appreciated how they portrayed the characters in that film. But again, the super dark tones of this war torn father who struggles with depression and almost strangles his son in one scene, really made it so that I can't appreciate the original without associating it with this dark imagery. And I'm just not sure if I want to watch another live action take on a beloved children's property that depicts the harshness of reality, to only shoehorn in some hand fisted moral at the end. Again, I'm not saying that those movies are inherently bad, but I just wish we'd get some new creative films that kids can adore too. But Disney especially seems set on taking their older properties and turning them into gritty live action films.

text: Number 15: Burger king foot lettuce. The last thing you'd want in your Burger King burger is someone's foot fungus. But as it turns out, that might be what you get. A 4channer uploaded a photo anonymously to the site showcasing his feet in a plastic bin of lettuce. With the statement: "This is the lettuce you eat at Burger King." Admittedly, he had shoes on. But that's even worse.  The post went live at 11:38 PM on July 16, and a mere 20 minutes later, the Burger King in question was alerted to the rogue employee. At least, I hope he's rogue. How did it happen? Well, the BK employee hadn't removed the Exif data from the uploaded photo, which suggested the culprit was somewhere in Mayfleld Heights, Ohio. This was at 11:47. Three minutes later at 11:50, the Burger King branch address was posted with wishes of happy unemployment. 5 minutes later, the news station was contacted by another 4channer. And three minutes later, at 11:58, a link was posted: BK's "Tell us about us" online forum. The foot photo, otherwise known as exhibit A, was attached. Cleveland Scene Magazine contacted the BK in question the next day. When questioned, the breakfast shift manager said "Oh, I know who that is. He's getting fired." Mystery solved, by 4chan. Now we can all go back to eating our fast food in peace.

text: An ottoman is a form of couch which usually has a head but no back, though sometimes it has neither. It may have square or semicircular ends, and as a rule it is what upholsterers call "overstuffed‚Äù‚Äîthat is to say no wood is visible.[1] It may be used as a stool, footstool,[2][3] coffee table,[4] or as an alternative to a sofa.[5] Ottomans are often sold as coordinating furniture with armchairs or gliders.[6] An ottoman can also be known as a footstool,[7] tuffet,[8] hassock,[9] "Sitee",[citation needed] or pouffe.[10][11] "Ottoman" may also denote an upholstered seat without a back or arms, but one that usually serves as storage, with the seat hinged to form a lid.

text: Apparently I‚Äôm in the minority, but I think this movie looks kind of bad. The CGI looks cold and creepy. And the plot is about a too-serious adult who needs to learn to have fun? And then beloved magical creatures leave their forest and cause mayhem in the city? That‚Äôs the plot of The Smurfs! I love Winnie the Pooh. I went through a latent Winnie the Pooh phase in middle school specifically because I was depressed and pined for the simplicity of childhood innocence. In spirit, I should love this movie. But if the trailer is to be believed, this is the most cliche approach you could have taken to telling this story.

text: Imagine if the writers gave this movie a dark twist. The whole movie, adult Christopher did not take his medication. He left as a child to be cured of his "madness" at an institution like Bedlam. As an adult, he took meds to stop the hallucinations of talking stuffed animals. Suddenly, while on the train to the family cottage in the country, he realized that he had forgotten his pills. He rushed back to their flat in London. That was when he started seeing Pooh and his friends again. Later on in the film, Christopher learned that his daughter inherited the illness.The moral of the story is don't trust Big Pharm. Embrace your childhood.   Anyway, trailer made me teary-eyed. Look forward to seeing the movie.

text: The film looks like it might actually be good, but it's a bit difficult to see behind the - surprisingly cheap looking- trailer. I sincerely hope we get another trailer that will let the film shine through more.

The idea that Robin has to return to his past childhood friends in order to see what is missing seems like a wonderful idea. I think my only complaint is the cgi look of the characters. I'm not sure if I like that toy looking quality to them. I also think it would be nice if their colors were brighter to be more like the later adaption style of Winnie the Pooh and not so much the book illustration. My favorite other than Pooh is Tigger. He was my very first stuffed animal, and it‚Äôs my dog‚Äôs name because he likes to jump on people a lot üòÇ. And hearing Jim Cummings voice as Pooh Bear and Tigger again just brings back so many memories. I‚Äôm going to take my parents and sister to see this since they love Winnie the Pooh almost as much as me. I‚Äôm probably going to cry at this movie even more than I did with ‚ÄúPete‚Äôs Dragon‚Äù.  ‚ÄúGood afternoon, Pooh Bear. If it is a good afternoon, which I doubt.‚Äù  ‚ÄúAnd then, we can all do the Whoop-de-Dooper-Loop-de-Looper-Ali-Ooper-Bounce!‚Äù ‚ÄúThe Whoop-de-Dooper... what kind of bounce?‚Äù  ‚ÄúThe wonderful thing about Tiggers is I‚Äôm only one. I‚ÄôM the only one!‚Äù  ‚ÄúT-T-F-N! Ta-ta for now!‚Äù  ‚ÄúOh, d-d-dear! Oh, d-d-d-deary, dear, dear!‚Äù  ‚ÄúThink, think, think.‚Äù  ‚ÄúI always get to where I‚Äôm going as long as I‚Äôm walking away from where I‚Äôve been.‚Äù  ‚ÄúPeople say nothing is impossible, but I do nothing everyday.‚Äù  ‚ÄúOh, stuff and fluff!‚Äù  ‚ÄúOh, bother.‚Äù  ‚ÄúSilly ol‚Äô bear!‚Äù  ‚ÄúIf there‚Äôs ever a tomorrow where we‚Äôre not together, there‚Äôs something you must remember. You‚Äôre braver than you believe, stronger than you seem, and smarter than you think. Even if we‚Äôre apart, I‚Äôll always be with you.‚Äù  ‚ÄúI‚Äôll be back. As long as you‚Äôre here. Promise me you‚Äôll be here. Always? Even when I‚Äôm a hundred?‚Äù ‚ÄúHow old shall I be then?‚Äù Ninety-nine.‚Äù ‚ÄúI promise.‚Äù ‚ÄúForever and ever?‚Äù ‚ÄúYes, Christopher Robin. text: The animals look more like the original illustrations in the books from the 20s by E. H. Shepard, not the ones we're more accustomed to, which were created by Disney illustrators during the early 70s.  I think that's why some may be a bit freaked out.  The movie obviously takes place a while ago, and the producers were trying to create the look and simplicity of old-fashioned toys which is pretty much what they did here. I like their look somehow‚Ä¶  there's sort of  this mixture between the old Disney cartoons that I (and all of us)  grew up with, and are familiar, and the earliest illustrations that sort of ground them in their origins and brings it all full circle. This looks like it'll be a lovely movie. ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è

text: I absolutely LOVE THIS MOVIE!!!¬† Haven't seen it, yet, but the trailer is so AWESOME!!¬† When it comes out, I'll definitely pay to see it!¬† This movie is for anyone who has ever had that one FAVORITE toy, or even group of toys, that just made their childhood far better than it could've ever been without them!¬† Mine is a little Garfield that one of my teachers bought me and brought to the hospital when I was there getting my appendix out.¬† She actually cared enough to get me a gift.¬† She brought Garfield to me in a little, wrinkled, brown, paper bag.¬† I thought it was a Big Mac, at first, but was overjoyed that it was what it was!!¬† I STILL have that Garfield, to this day.¬† He sits in his place of honor, on my bedside table, next to the clock.¬† I got him when I was just 13, and now, I am 47!¬† He is 24 years old and I have always remembered him!¬† He helped me through a very abusive childhood.¬† Thank you, Garfield!

text: Not to get too deep or anything, but I love that this movie seems to understand the simple and slightly askew philosophy of Winnie the Pooh. What he said wasn't deep, but the way he said it and the way he was always sold it. He's a being of pure optimism and ignorance and though the 'People say nothing is impossible, but I do nothing every day line' is just about perfect, there is one that I think perfectly encapsulates who and what Winnie the Pooh always was to me:  "I suppose it's where it needs to be." "That's a silly explanation." "Thank you."  That is the Winnie the Pooh that I loved as a child and never stopped loving.

Metanoia); Strong's #3341; This Greek word is a compound word derived from meta, meaning "after" and suggesting some type of change, and nous, meaning "mind." text: This is Disney's trial run for Ewan McGregor to see if he is ready to handle Obi-Wan A Star Wars Story. If this movie does anywhere near decent at the box office, it's all but confirmed he will be reprising the role. The film will cover his time in exile between ep 3 and 4, protecting Luke from harm, and maybe we'll even get a live action version of the duel between him and Maul from Rebels. You're crazy if you don't think at some point during the filming of this Disney didn't go *nudge nudge* "So Ewan, about that Obi-Wan movie.." Too much money for Disney not to do this. They also need something Star Wars related to milk for cash after ep 9 and the new trilogy concludes.  In other news, the trailer looks very promising. Love Pooh!

text: I have watched mostly every single movie of my childhood that has came from either stories or just the fact that Legends were told from books. Out of all of them I have been waiting for Winnie the Pooh to get a live-action movie because after finding out that Christopher Robin in real life gave up on his old childhood friend it truly broke my heart but looking at this makes me feel like this movie might give Christopher Robin some closure and maybe even from feels from people who knew him even if they were young or even if they were too small to understand what he was about..... I believe that in heaven Christopher Robin might think that Winnie the Pooh might have been still the thing that ruined his life but I hope that after he feels how many people love what he has brought us from the children that have been born watching Winnie the Pooh or have a stuffed animal of his..... To the children that will go up to watch the videos of Winnie the Pooh or even be read to sleep from his father's work..... He will understand how much people can relate to him and see that Winnie the Pooh will always be a friend of his and a friend of Millions.

text: I want this to be a mix between The little Prince (the book) and Hook. I don't like the idea that his imaginary friends are actual real life beings. It kinda undercuts the idea these were imaginary characters Christopher Robin made using stuffed animals, and that talking to them again is him trying to escape from his tired adult life and finding what it means to be a kid again. Imagine if the whole movie took place in the hundred acre wood. Maybe time has changed it. Perhaps it was sold or tore down, and talking to his once beloved friends is a means to cope and accept change while also knowing that his childhood and the good times will be forever remembered. It would ten times more emotional that way, but by the looks of it Pooh is interacting with other characters making them seem like real life people. Both Hook and The little Prince deal with recapturing childhood as adults, and both leave it to interpretation whether the plot actually happened  or if it was all in the imagination of the main character and were better for it.

text: As a parent, I feel like everywhere I turn, someone is warning me about the dangers of letting my children watch TV. While I agree that it can be harmful in large doses, honestly, what really matters to me is just making sure that when my children do watch TV, they‚Äôre watching shows that impart some sort of positive value into their lives. This also means steering them away from programs that might affect them negatively, which is why I never allow my children to watch anything featuring Winnie the Pooh, the fat virgin.  If you‚Äôre unfamiliar, Winnie the Pooh is a brainless bear who lives in the forest and slowly makes the world bad. He has beady serpent eyes and zero genitals, which is something we know because he never wears any pants or undergarments. In fact, he‚Äôs practically bragging about not having a penis. But even if he did have a penis, he wouldn‚Äôt know it, because his fat belly would keep him from seeing anything below his sad bear tits. It makes me mad just thinking about it. This bear, he just wanders around eating honey out of a jar with his bare hands like a fat savage. I hate it.  One thing that can be assumed about the dickless sad sack called Winnie the Pooh is that he is a virgin. He clearly has never fucked. He is a simpering, high-voiced virgin who spends all his time leering at a little boy named Christopher. It‚Äôs disgusting. I don‚Äôt want my kids being exposed to that. I‚Äôm not going to be like, ‚ÄúHey, kids, come watch the emasculated bear with the scary fingerless hands who‚Äôs never fucked a day in his life and who is obsessed with a little boy of a different species.‚Äù That‚Äôd be irresponsible and gross.  For those who are unfamiliar with Winnie the Pooh, he is a simpering, high-voiced virgin who spends all his time leering at a little boy named Christopher.   ‚ÄúBut what do you let your kids watch?‚Äù you might ask. I‚Äôd much rather my kids watch the fuck machine named Big Bird. Big Bird is the towering human bird from PBS who you can tell is just constantly fucking. He‚Äôs got that swagger. There are a lot of good lessons children can learn from a major-league pussy-crusher like Big Bird, such as the importance of confidence, courage, and friendship.  Winnie the Pooh, on the other hand, wouldn‚Äôt know the first thing about courage. If he were on United Airlines Flight 93, for example, not only would he have not joined the revolt against the terrorists, but he probably would‚Äôve gotten down on his yellow knees and sucked the terrorists‚Äô cocks one by one. ‚ÄúOh, bother!‚Äù he would shrug as the al-Qaeda operatives drilled the back of his throat with their pube-slathered ding-dongs.  What a coward, this pathetic bear.  I cannot fathom how any parent could ever willingly expose their children to trash like Winnie the Pooh. It seems like a guaranteed recipe to ensure that your kids grow up to be pitiful, dead-eyed perverts who will never know the heavenly joys of fucking. If you want your kids to grow up to be brave and smart, you should let them watch either the impressive sex duck Big Bird, the cunning potato named Arthur, or Babar the indoor elephant. Winnie the Pooh is a walking disease, and if I ever catch my kids watching him, I will spank them with my belt. And if you‚Äôre a good parent, you will do the same.

text: I really hope that this movie doesn‚Äôt focus on Winnie the Pooh and the gang, instead of Christopher Robin. Though Christopher is literally the thing that inspired the whole Winnie the Pooh franchise, the title is ‚ÄúCHRISTOPHER ROBIN‚Äù Not ‚ÄúWINNIE THE POOH‚Äù I wouldn‚Äôt mind if they showed The Acer woods gang individually without Christopher for a _few_ shots. Christopher Robin, I‚Äôm pretty sure is the protagonist, not Pooh Bear. But I highly doubt that they‚Äôll show Christopher most of the time, because the only shots you see with him would seem pretty boring to kids; they want to see the animals talk, and interact with humans! But if they mess that up to make an excuse to show off their cgi, then that‚Äôll be my complaint. Don‚Äôt get me wrong, I love Winnie the Pooh, he‚Äôs my favorite, it‚Äôs just that he isn‚Äôt the protagonist in this film. I‚Äôm also *really* worried that Kanga, roo, and Rabbit won‚Äôt talk. There are also some minor errors at about 0:35, 1:11, 1:45, etc.  When you get a chance, could you fix that? text: Being a huge fan of Bruce Lee and Brandon Lee, the writings and wisdom of Bruce Lee and his books, the Tao of Jeet Kune Do has been so inspiring.   If this hasn't already been mentioned, please find and read the books the Tao of Pooh and the Te of Piglet.  I always read Winnie the Pooh "children's" books they're so inspiring, fun, magical and full of wisdom!  https://www.just-pooh.com/tao.html  "Winnie the Pooh has a certain way about him, a way of doing things which has made him the world's most beloved bear. And Pooh's Way, as Benjamin Hoff brilliantly demonstrates, seems strangely close to the ancient Chinese principles of Taoism. The 'Tao of Pooh' explains Taoism by Winnie the Pooh and explains Winnie the Pooh by Taoism. It makes you understand what A.A. Milne probably meant when he said he didn't write the Pooh-books for children in the first place."   Winnie the Pooh is named after Winnipeg! Super proud Winnipegger here!  https://www.just-pooh.com/history.html  In addition to Winnie the Pooh and his friends, my favorite is Eeyore!  Can't wait to see this film!

text: I‚Äôm not sure if this will be as incredible as Spike Jonze‚Äôs adaptation of ‚ÄòWhere the Wild Things Are‚Äô, but I am very, very pleased at both:  A. The adult aspect of the screenwriting and it‚Äôs transcendence into fantasy-realism (like Big Fish ‚Äî which this trailer reminds me of), and  B.) The decision to stray away from Disney‚Äôs animated adaptation of the characters and use the old 1926 E. H. Shepard illustrations.   Bold move, but it doesn‚Äôt seem that kids today particularly read or watch the Pooh novels/animated serials, so taking a more modern adult approach may be simply because those who grew up with these character are now older, and have experienced the anxiety of Piglet, the depression of Eeyore, and the absentmindedness and innocent oblivion of Mr. Pooh.

So please. if your considering going to this , but you read some critic , that most likely needs a laxative from a hard life , review , take into consideration the impact  Winnie The Pooh had on you when you were a kid.  Heck the movie , Christopher Robin , brought me back in such a wonderful way , that I remembered the book *The Te of Piglet* by _Benjamin Hoff_  That was back when I decided , or life decided for me, that change was needed .  I would practice stretching and breathing and think of all the zen like things Pooh would say .   During the whole time I was watching Christopher Robin my spirit was smiling toes to fingertips . So don't listen to those who only want to say negative things about a heart warming experience you can have with your children. There is a song called _Cat's in the Cradle_ , and that does happen all too soon. There is the character _Madeline_ ,  and  _" Your life is happening now, right in front of you "_  Here's a song from my childhood that I loved and still do. I'ts from  _Loggins&Messina_  called  *_House at Pooh Corner_*  Hope you enjoy. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qlSLeIMgr9E  Christopher Robin and I walked along Under branches lit up by the moon. Posing our questions to owl and eeyore As our days disappeared all too soon. But I've wandered much further today than I should And I can't seem to find my way back to the wood. So, help me if you can I've got to get Back to the house at Pooh corner by one. You;d be surprised there's so much to be done, Count all the bees in the hive, Chase all the clouds from the sky. Back to the days of Christopher Robin and Pooh. Winnie the Pooh doesn't know what to do, Got a honey jar stuck on his nose. He came to me asking help and advice And from here no one knows where he goes. So I sent him to ask of te Owl if he's there, How to loosen a jar from the nose of a bear So, help me if you can I've got to get Back to the house at Pooh corner by one You'd be surprised there's so much to be done, Count all the bees in the hive, Chase all the clouds from the sky . Back to the days of Christopher Robin and Pooh, Back to the days of Christopher Robin, Back to the ways of Pooh  _best wishes all_

text: This movie was awesome. I was the only single adult in the theater for a Sunday Matinee. It felt a little odd, but I didn't let it stop me...and I'm so glad. No political BS, no preaching or ranting, and they didn't "mess" with the characters that we know so well. Just sweet family entertainment. Anyone else out there in a similar situation needs to just go and see it. This is the kind of movie Disney ought to be putting out, and we need to show them that with our wallets. Don't get me wrong...I like T&A and blood and guts as much as the next guy, but we need this too. I think Walt would be proud of this one, and that's saying something.

text: Winnie the Pooh is a honey-loving plush toy bear who lives in the Hundred-Acre Wood and is voiced by Jim Cummings.  Piglet is a toy pig in the Hundred-Acre Wood who is afraid of everything but has a big heart and is voiced by Nick Mohammed.  Eeyore is a toy donkey in the Hundred-Acre Wood who always loses his tail and talks with a deep depressing voice and tone and is voiced by Brad Garrett.  Kanga is a toy kangaroo in the Hundred-Acre Wood who is the mother of Roo and is voiced by Sophie Okonedo.  Roo is a toy joey in the Hundred-Acre Wood who is the child of Kanga and is voiced by Sara Sheen.  Rabbit is a rabbit who is a neat freak and a vegetable farmer in the Hundred-Acre Wood and is voiced by Peter Capaldi.  Tigger is a toy tiger who lives in the Hundred-Acre Wood who loves to bounce on his tail like a spring and is voiced by Jim Cummings.  Owl is the wise owl of the Hundred-Acre Wood and is voiced by Toby Jones.

text: This is the live action Winnie The Pooh movie that we have been waiting for, actually, I thought I would never see a live-action Winnie the Pooh, well I was wrong and Disney does it right. This movie has the charm of a Winnie The Pooh and Ewan McGregor is excellent as Christopher Robin, the whole cast was great and to have Jim Cummings do the voice of Pooh and Tigger was great. This is a great family film and anybody who is a Pooh fan will love this movie and who doesn't really know the character will fall in love with it. The CGI is great in this movie and I like how they make Pooh and his friends look like stuffed animals and there is some reference to The Many Adventures Of Winnie The Pooh in this movie spoiler like the scene where Christopher and Pooh throw sticks in the river off the bridge and some other recognizable stuff. The acting, story, and directing is great in this movie. This is a well-made film and hopefully, it gets the praise it deserves. And what would a Winnie The Pooh movie be without the Tigger song and the Winnie The Pooh song? I would have been a little disappointed if those songs were not in the movie would it make it worse, no but it is icing on the cake. P.S. Bronte Carmichael was terrific as Madeline Robin, Christopher's daughter. If you have not seen this movie then I recommend you do. This movie is Cinematastic rating 5/5

text: Girlfriend Made me watch this on Netflix with her yesterday. I'm a guy about to turn 30 who's worked in loud profanity filled industrial type jobs  where everybody makes the raunchiest, nastiest, and poor taste jokes you could ever imagine since I was 16 years old.  After so many years that stuff starts to rub off on you and it makes you cold, hard, and sometimes very insensitive.  I'm almost embarrassed to admit the childhood innocence in this movie and  the relate-able story of Christopher Robins transition to adulthood along with remembering long forgotten early childhood memories of my dad reading me Winnie The Pooh story books before bed made for a very tearful experience lol.

text: I love how so many of us grew up watching Winnie the Pooh regardless of how old we are, and how we're all touched by the love and nostalgia we feel looking at these familiar characters. We hearken back to a simpler time without cares and worries, and bask in the playful and whimsical story of Pooh and friends. Although we're older now and have real responsibilities, maybe we ought to try to be a little more fun, a little more innocent and playful, a little more lively...it just might make a world of difference in the troubled times upon us.

text: I've thinking, and maybe we all need to be like childs even when grown up, because when kids, we all have what we need to open a door to a new workd where everything is possible: Innocence, Imagination, and Optimism, things that may create a better world by showing us hpw it can be, but sadly also things that may leave us if we let adulthood affect or way of seeing the world. And Pooh represents the wisdom that comes with childhood, because he has a lot of innocence, he is optimistic, and quite imaginative, and, thanms to that, he never forgets what is really important yet he gets what he eants, and shates it with others, he manages to see a light in every darkness, and best of all, he's always happy thanks to that. And with that imagination, optimism, and innocence, we could destroy all the hate and fear that is destroying our world, and maybe even destroying them from history, as if hate and fear never existed. In simple words, we should all be like Pooh, because it would create a better world  PD: Thos guys with Down Syndrome are very luckily.

Success is measured in money and possessions , not by happiness, empathy, love and compassion, ideas and stories.  Childhood is where we all belong.  When our childhood is over, that‚Äôs where we took a wrong turn. Never grow up.

text: I don't know why I heard bad things about this movie from some people. I just watched it and it made me cry hard multiple times. Crazy thing is I watched Pooh a couple of times as a little kid and then unlike other Kid movies never rewatched it again later in my life. So in a way I forgot about it, even though I never forgot the characters, the words and all of that. Maybe that made me connect to the movie even more. Apart from me being able to understand the adult Christopher Robin so well that is. This movie is definitely the best thing Disney has gotten out of the whole "we're gonna get all our old IPs out and make a new/ different version out of it" thing they are doing. The animals look perfect. The story brings something new and beautiful to the table while also being true to the original. All while hitting themes that are just incredibly relatable and havin Ewan McGregor with a great performance in it.
